<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK's Rifkind Welcomes Partnership for Peace Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK's Rifkind Welcomes Partnership for Peace Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505165894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1611 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels May 25 TASS -- Russian Defence Minister 
Pavel Grachev met with British Defence Secretary Malcolm Rifkind 
at the NATO headquarters in Brussels on Wednesday to discuss 
Russia's concept of partnership with NATO. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS, Grachev said that European 
security is not only NATO's prerogative. Security should be 
ensured by joint effort of all political and military 
structures, he added. 
  Speaking about bilateral cooperation, Grachev noted that an 
agreement has been reached to send to Britain about 60 junior 
Russian officers for military training. 
  Additionally, working groups will be set up this year to 
study prospects for holding joint Russian-British military 
manoeuvres next year. 
  Rifkind expressed satisfaction with the fact that Russia has 
confirmed its intention to join the Partnership for Peace 
programme. 
  In his address to the NATO leaders earlier today Grachev 
said 
that Russia is ready to develop broad and constructive 
cooperation with NATO and called for devising an "active 
mechanism" of bilateral consultations on all problems concerning 
European and global security. 
  Grachev said that "Russia is ready to develop genuine and 
all 
embracing strategic cooperation with NATO. NATO's partnership 
for peace programme should play a role in this process." 
  However, he stressed that the programme "is not a 
comprehensive answer to the realities of the new epoch" and is 
only the first step towards building a new strategic alliance in 
the name of peace and security. 
  Russia is interested in broader relations with NATO to 
correspond its (Russia's) weight and position in the system of 
international relations, Grachev said. He emphasised that 
Russia does not claim any privileges, but is seeking to develop 
and expand the very concept of partnership between the East and 
West. 
  He said Russia is also ready to develop cooperation with 
NATO 
in coordination of military policies, peace-keeping operations, 
military planning and training, as well as disarmament, arms 
control, conversion, non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and 
nature protection. 

</TEXT>

