<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Orders Reassurance To Be Issued on Crimea Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Orders Reassurance To Be Issued on Crimea Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505173994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1611 
GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2505173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 25 May -- The numerous alarming reports 
coming in from the Crimea are creating an agitated mood among 
the population of the Crimea itself, as well as that of Ukraine 
and Russia. 
  Meanwhile, the summer vacation period is approaching. The 
Crimea is known to be a holiday resort traditionally popular 
with the residents of Russia, Ukraine, and other CIS states. If 
a "frontline" atmosphere is artificially created, hundreds of 
thousands of people may succumb to groundless fear and will thus 
be left without a place to spend their vacation in. 
  Russian President Boris Yeltsin has instructed his press 
service to make it clear to the public that the situation in the 
Crimea is giving no cause for concern. The calm atmosphere and 
the entire infrastructure required for normal peaceful rest are 
being maintained in the Crimea. The president's press service 
gave this message to the ITAR-TASS agency. 

</TEXT>

