<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Great Difficulties' Seen in Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Great Difficulties' Seen in Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505155094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1456 
GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2505155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 25 May -- The Ukrainian delegation at the 
Moscow intergovernmental talks on settling the problem of the 
Black Sea Fleet has agreed to continue work on one of the four 
Russian options for dividing the fleet which had earlier been 
rejected. As a reserve, the Russian party has one more option 
-- the "presidential" -- which is still to be revealed. 
  An ITAR-TASS correspondent has learned on the sidelines of 
the talks between the Russian and Ukrainian government heads 
that the attempt to harmonize the positions of the parties, 
which are at times mutually exclusive, is experiencing great 
difficulties. The talks process has already gone on for three 
days. The chief stumbling-block lies in the conflicting 
approaches of Moscow and Kiev to the principle of separate bases 
for the national fleets. 
  Both delegations have held repeated consultations with their 
presidents using the telephone "hot" line. Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and acting Ukrainian Prime Minister 
Yefim Zvyagilskiy met several times today. However the main 
work is being done by the working group of experts. 
  It is expected that the sides will draw up the final text of 
the intergovernment agreement on beginning the division of the 
Black Sea Fleet. If this happens, the document will be signed 
by Viktor Chernomyrdin and Yefim Zvyagilskiy, the heads of the 
delegations of Russia and Ukraine at the talks. 
  One way or the other, the talks will end this evening, since 
Viktor Chernomyrdin leaves for an official visit to China after 
2000. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

