<H3> <TI>   Delegations To Meet in 10-12 Days </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegations To Meet in 10-12 Days </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505192494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1826 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505192494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian and Ukrainian officials meeting in Moscow to 
discuss the future of the Black Sea Fleet have failed to reach 
any agreement after three days of intensive negotiations. 
  Speaking afterwards, Ukrainian Vice Premier Valeriy Shmarov 
said that although the two sides had toiled in two shifts for 
three days, there was still some work to be done because a 
sharing out of the Fleet demanded great attention. He said the 
two delegations were close to agreement on Wednesday, but had to 
break off the talks to "clarify some technicalities". 
  Shmarov said the two delegations were due to meet in about 
10 
or 12 days to sign an agreement on the first stage of sharing 
the Fleet. 
  Russia's envoy Yuriy Dubinin has pointed to the constructive 
atmosphere prevailing at the talks. He was confident that all 
of the remaining technicalities would have been resolved to 
enable the prime ministers on both sides to sign the final 
agreement in 10 or 12 days from now. 

</TEXT>

