<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fleet Exercises Seen as Successful </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fleet Exercises Seen as Successful </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2505120794 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM2505120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast: Video report by V. Tarasov, A. </F>
Vozhzhov, and A. Lebedev, identified by caption] 
  [Text] [Tarasov] Four days of work out on the high seas 
have seen the ships of the Black Sea Fleet running through 
various combat training exercises to fend off underwater, 
surface, and air attacks from any likely adversary. The 
exercises were led by Vice Admiral Vitaliy Laryenov, first 
deputy commander of the Black Sea Fleet. In his judgment, the 
sailors coped well with the tasks set. But in general the 
results of the exercises would have been far better but for the 
regular disruption of drills and combat training due to 
shortages of financial and material resources. It is indicative 
that these latest exercise, completed without any hiccups, 
involved inducted personnel. As we know, nowadays warship crews 
are made up equally of citizens drafted both from Russia and 
Ukraine. Nevertheless, according to the sailors themselves, the 
long promised carve-up of the Black Sea Fleet is inevitable. So 
what is required now is the most vigorous action on the part of 
top Ukrainian and Russian officials. 

</TEXT>

