<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peace-Keeping Forces To Arrive in Abkhazia in Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peace-Keeping Forces To Arrive in Abkhazia in Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505131494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1047 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The CIS peace-keeping forces, mostly composed of the 
Russian military contingent, are to be introduced into the zone 
of the Abkhazian conflict before June 10. The latest date for 
their deployment is June 15. The operation will be supervised 
by Deputy Commander of the Russian infantry troops, 
Lieutenant-General Aleksandr Sokolov. Interfax learned this 
from sources in one of the delegations currently negotiating in 
Moscow on deployment of the peace-keeping forces. The 
negotiations are expected to end today. 
  The Abkhazian delegation is headed by Abkhazian Defense 
Minister Sultan Sosnaliyev. Georgian Defense Minister Varden 
Nadibaidze leads the Georgian delegation. Russia acts as a 
mediator and is represented by high-ranking military officers. 
  In accordance with the agreements reached on May 14, the 
peace- keeping forces will be deployed in the security zone 
which will lay on the Inguri River after the Georgian and 
Abkhazian troops are withdrawn twelve kilometers from it. The 
size of the peace forces is expected to be about 2,500-3,000 
servicemen. 
  Interfax learned that a group of Russian officers may leave 
for Abkhazia on Thursday in order to define specific regions for 
deployment of the peace-keeping forces. 

</TEXT>

