<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Drops Into East Siberian Sea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Drops Into East Siberian Sea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605102194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0956 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605102194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Semyon Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 26 TASS -- The Cosmos 2281 satellite 
fired off with a Tsiklon-3 three stage booster from the Plesetsk 
cosmodrome on Wednesday, failed to come into orbit. 
  ITAR-TASS learnt at the press centre of Russian Space 
Military Forces that the switch-off of the propulsion unit and 
the separation of the third stage were not registered. 
  According to calculations, the satellite as well as the 
second and the third stages of the booster dropped in the area 
of the East Siberian Sea where the fall of the second stage had 
been planned. 
  The launching was made in the interests of the Russian 
Defence Ministry. An interdepartmental commission has been set 
up to examine possible reasons for the failure. 

</TEXT>

