</HEADER>

<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Azerbaijan Blamed For Cease-Fire Violations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Azerbaijan Blamed For Cease-Fire Violations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2505183894 Yerevan Radio Yerevan in Azeri 1330 GMT 25 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2505183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Radio Yerevan </F>
<F P=105>  Azeri </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dear listeners, we now present a report on the 
latest situation in the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic [NKR] and the 
border between Armenia and Azerbaijan. 
  We welcome the fact that the combat operations in the 
confrontation zone have been suspended. The agreement for a 
cease-fire has rarely been violated, but Azerbaijan has to be 
blamed for the violations of the agreement. That Republic's 
military units have intermittently fired on various points of 
the Armenian front line. The NKR defense units have refrained 
from returning the fire. 
  Regrettably, Azerbaijan has violated the cease-fire. The NKR 
Defense Army Headquarters Press Service has disclosed that 
Azerbaijan's military units tried to capture a strategically 
important hill in the Gadrutskiy and Fizulinskiy sector of the 
front line at about 0300. The NKR defense units repulsed the 
attack. No one was hurt on the Armenian side. 
  The Armenian Ministry of Defense Information Center has 
informed us that the situation on the border between Armenia and 
Azerbaijan has been relatively peaceful. No incident has 
occurred in that region. 
  We hope that a completely peaceful situation will be 
established on the border as soon as possible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

