<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Defends Human Rights Memorandum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Defends Human Rights Memorandum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2605095494 Tallinn ETA in English 0736 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2605095494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From 26 May EESTI SENUMID, PAEVALEHT, p 1; "News Bulletin" </F>
No. 101/94] 
  [Text] Thursday, May 26 -- Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev defended the memorandum submitted by Russia and declared 
that Russia's attempts to develop "friendly and goodneighbourly 
relations with Estonia include the use of harsh terms". He also 
predicted that even harsher language would be used at his 
meeting with the Russian speakers in Tallinn. 
  The foreign minister told the listeners in the Slavic 
Culture 
Centre that Russia is developing a government programme for the 
aid and protection of the compatriots living abroad. A special 
commission will be formed, which could operate more efficiently 
than the Foreign Ministry with its diplomatic protocol. Kozyrev 
added that Russia is particularly interested in the pensioners' 
issue and problems of privatisation and enterprise. 
  He declared that the border issues will not be discussed and 
demanded that all retired military, including former KGB and GRU 
intelligence officers, must receive social guarantees as well as 
automatic citizenship. Describing the situation in Estonia, 
Kozyrev commented that, speaking as a private individual rather 
than a diplomat, he would have to ask for the ladies to leave 
the hall. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

