<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vilnius Reports Baltic Air Force Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vilnius Reports Baltic Air Force Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505194594 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
1200 GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2505194594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lithuanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The air force commanders of the three Baltic states 
have agreed on cooperation in air space control and the training 
of air force pilots. An agreement signed at the Lithuanian 
Meskuiciai air force base confirms the intent to set up a joint 
air space control system. Representatives of the Baltic states 
note technical and financial advantages of such integration and 
the intention to join corresponding NATO structures. It will 
probably take 5 to 10 years to create a joint Baltic air space 
control system. 
  The Baltic representatives also decided to set up a joint 
training center for air force pilots in Lithuania. Estonian air 
force pilots took their first training flights on Lithuanian 
planes at Meskuiciai base today. 
  Lithuania's air force, with four L-39 jet training fighters 
of Czech production, two transport L-410 planes donated by 
Germany, and several dozen AN-2 planes and helicopters, is the 
strongest among the Baltic states and the most experienced. 
  Two of the four Lithuanian jet planes and one helicopter 
will 
demonstrate their combat skill on Saturday [28 May] on a 
military airfield near Riga during celebrations devoted to the 
75th anniversary of the Latvian air force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

