<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Vows `All Necessary Measures' To Be Taken </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Vows `All Necessary Measures' To Be Taken </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2505120794 Kiev DEMOKRATYCHNA UKRAYINA in Ukrainian 24 May 
94 pp 1, 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU2505120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev DEMOKRATYCHNA UKRAYINA </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Undated "Statement by the Press Center of Ukraine's </F>
Ministry of Foreign Affairs"] 
  [Text] On 20 May 1994, the Crimean Supreme Council adopted 
the law "On the Restoration of the Constitutional Principles of 
the Crimean Republic's Statehood" having thereby made an attempt 
to restore the Crimean Constitution in its 6 May 1992 variant. 
This law is unconstitutional and illegal. It leads to an 
exacerbation of interethnic tension on the peninsula and in 
Ukraine as a whole and raises the question of the legal status 
of the Crimean Republic as a constituent part of Ukraine. This 
creates a direct threat to Ukraine's territorial integrity and 
peace and stability in the region. 
  In this connection, Ukraine's Minister of Foreign Affairs 
A.M. Zlenko sent letters to the UN secretary general, the 
chairman of the Security Council, the chairman of the CSCE, 
NATO's general secretary, leaders of other international 
organizations, and ministers of foreign affairs of foreign 
countries. In his letters, the head of Ukraine's external 
political department stresses, in particular, that this illegal 
decision, provoked by the irresponsible course pursued by the 
present Crimean leadership and aimed at undermining Ukraine's 
constitutional power and its territorial integrity cannot be 
qualified in any other terms than an open attempt on the part of 
separatist forces to weaken the internal political stability in 
Ukraine and provoke tension in the Ukrainian- Russian relations. 
This creates a threat to peace and stability in the region and 
in the whole of Europe, something which may have far-reaching 
negative consequences, in view of the present complicated 
situation in this part of the continent. 
  Today those European countries, which are participants in 
the 
CSCE, have admitted the exceptional importance unconditionally 
to maintain and strengthen the principles of territorial 
integrity and inviolability of existing borders, as a guarantee 
for European peace and security. Such separatist aspirations on 
the part of the leadership of the Crimean Republic may result in 
further erosion of these fundamental principles underlying 
European stability. In the case of a further escalation of the 
situation as a result of the irresponsible steps by the 
extremist forces in the Crimea, Ukraine reserves the right to 
take all the necessary measures for an unconditional protection 
of the state's territorial integrity in conformity with its 
constitution and current legislation and with an adherence to 
the norms of international law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63950 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov102_f_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-102 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister's Appeal to Crimea Internal Affairs Bodies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister's Appeal to Crimea Internal Affairs Bodies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505224394 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 2145 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505224394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kiev, 25 May -- Ukrainian Internal Affairs Minister 
Andriy Vasylyshyn has delivered an address to the leadership and 
all personnel of internal affairs agencies in Crimea. 
  The address reads, in particular: "The non-performance by 
the 
Crimean autonomy's authorities of the Ukrainian presidential 
directives and their deliberate disregard for Ukraine's 
Constitution and legislation are causing tension in the 
situation on the peninsula. All this is increasing pressure on 
the personnel of internal affairs agencies". 
  The Ukrainian Internal Affairs Ministry's collegium regrets 
that Crimean militiamen have to work "under difficult conditions 
which were artificially created," the minister points out. "We 
hope that the necessary decisions will be taken in the very near 
future, with the help of people's deputies of Ukraine and the 
Republic of Crimea, to stabilize the situation in Crimea." 
  The minister's appeal makes the following requests: 
  "To convey to members of staff our certainty that the bodies 
of internal affairs in Crimea will further remain within the 
single structure of the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Ukraine; 
  "To remain calm, confident, and loyal to their oath, to 
prevent the illegal use of arms, to treat citizens with respect, 
to strictly abide by laws when detaining citizens and making 
them answerable, and to prevent violations of the administrative 
legislation; 
  "To step up the struggle against crime and its most 
organized 
forms, to restore order in the streets and in public places, and 
in so doing to pay special attention to instructing special duty 
squads at a high professional level; 
  "To establish efficient interaction with the Main 
Directorate 
of the Security Service of Ukraine in Crimea, the procurator's 
office, the subunits of the National Guard and military units, 
and with other departments with the aim of improving adherence 
to law and order and legality in Crimea. 
  "Today peace and accord and citizens' security in Crimea are 
in your hands. Do not let yourselves get involved in political 
games." 

</TEXT>

