<DATE1>  25 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimea's Meshkov Sees Hope for Relations With Ukraine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimea's Meshkov Sees Hope for Relations With Ukraine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505173894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1701 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Karmalito] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol 25 May TASS -- Crimean President Yuriy 
Meshkov welcomed the latest developments in relations between 
the Crimea and Ukraine as hope-inspiring. 
  In an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS on Wednesday [25 
May], Meshkov said that the road to a compromise lies between 
the search for mutual understanding through bilateral 
negotiations and destructive policy pursued by Kiev. 
  Attempts by certain Ukrainian circles to provoke 
confrontation in the Crimea have failed. The negotiation 
process has been set in motion in order to bring together the 
positions of the two sides and find solutions to the existing 
problems and conflicts, Meshkov said. 
  He noted that Kiev continues its policy aimed at undermining 
executive power in the Crimea and destabilising the situation in 
the Republic. 
  Speaking about the decision to set up a working commission 
of 
Ukrainian and Crimean deputies to iron out disagreements, 
Meshkov expressed hope that the reached "elementary 
understanding" will be preserved. 
  "We have outlined an array of measures which both sides are 
ready to carry out. This is a step forward towards solving the 
existing problems," he added. 
  Asked about the Russian-Ukrainian talks on the Black Sea 
Fleet, the Crimean leader stressed that it would be "somewhat 
premature" to make assessments because there have been no 
official reports about the results of the talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

