Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Official Supports Power-Sharing Agreement With Kiev </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Official Supports Power-Sharing Agreement With Kiev </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505131794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1047 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Speaker of the Crimean Parliament Sergey Tsekov says 
Simferopol would be prepared to settle for a power sharing 
agreement with Kiev similar to that between Russia and 
Tatarstan. In a speech in Kiev late on Tuesday [24 May], he 
called for the adoption of one sweeping act to settle 
differences between Ukraine and Crimea. 
  Tsekov believes that the current tension follows not only 
Simferopol's recent decisions, but also a string of inconsistent 
political moves towards Crimea over the past 18 months. 
  He said that under the Republic's constitution of 6 May 
1992, 
Crimea is part of Ukraine and "that's all there is to it." 
  Parliamentary delegations on both sides ended talks in Kiev 
late on Tuesday by deciding to offer their legislatures to set 
up a joint working group to iron out differences. 
  In the meantime, a Ukrainian parliamentary commission has 
given the Crimean parliament three more days in which to repeal 
its resolution of last Friday to restore the Republic's 1992 
Constitution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

