<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-102 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Black Sea Fleet Assembly Not Linked to Crimean Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Black Sea Fleet Assembly Not Linked to Crimean Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505150794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1257 
GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2505150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 25 May -- The all-hands assembly of fleet 
commanders in Sevastopol, which, according to some Ukrainian 
mass media, provoked a negative response in Kiev, is not linked 
to the recent events in Crimea. According to the press center 
of the Black Sea Fleet, the commanders of formations, groupings, 
and units gathered today at the headquarters of the Black Sea 
Fleet to sum up the results of winter training. It was noted at 
a sitting of the military council that the fleet had 
successfully carried out its tasks in the past six months and 
was prepared to implement the programs of summer training. 
  The sitting of the military council devoted particular 
attention to the problem of injuries of servicemen during 
military training and operating the equipment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

