<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karasin Cited on Consular Consultations in Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karasin Cited on Consular Consultations in Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2605145194 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 26 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2605145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Gennadiy Charodeyev report: "Strict Visa Regulations No </F>
Obstacle to Chinese Criminals"] 
  [Text] The first Russian-Chinese consultations on consular 
questions in Beijing highly rated the joint actions of the two 
countries' law enforcement organs: It has become safe again to 
travel on the Beijing-Moscow train. IZVESTIYA was informed of 
this by Grigoriy Karasin, chief of the Foreign Ministry 
Information and Press Department. 
  According to Chinese special services data, over 70 
gangsters 
have been arrested. At least 140 violations of the law have 
been detected, including fights, robberies, rape, and 
hostage-taking on trains, as well as criminal offenses in Moscow. 
  The Chinese criminals decided to head for Russia and Hungary 
posing as businessmen and students. But few reached Budapest, 
they settled mainly in Siberia and the Far East. 
  The criminals' calculations proved correct. Because the 
Chinese victimized "their own," they did not attract the Russian 
militia's attention for a long time. Finally, after receiving 
the signal from China, the Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs 
sent a snatch squad onto the Beijing-Moscow train. The first 
four bandits were seized first and the militia arrested the 
others later. 
  Karasin reported that Moscow had spoken up for the Russian 
citizens detained in the PRC as "hostages." Russia's claims to 
the former USSR's property in 11 Chinese cities were also 
discussed. 
  An entry and exit visa procedure was introduced in January 
for Russians and Chinese holding general civilian foreign 
passports. But in recent months variant interpretations by the 
sides have emerged regarding the range of people who are also 
entitled to receive free multiple visas for official trips. It 
has been agreed to settle this question as well. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

