<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Ships May Use Russian Rivers Only in Daytime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Ships May Use Russian Rivers Only in Daytime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605155494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1046 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chinese ships, naval vessels included, will be 
allowed to navigate Russian border rivers in the Khabarovsk 
region's shores only in day time. Such a decision has been 
taken by the regional administration, which, pending the 
completion of appropriate bilateral diplomatic activity, imposed 
new rules for navigation on the border rivers. 
  From now on the Chinese side must inform a Russian border 
official about the number of ships, their names, and time of 
their passage one day in advance of sailing. However, vessels 
must keep clear of the shores, nor are they allowed to land 
people, accept them or cargoes on board, catch fish or engage in 
any research. 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry has been asked to speed up the 
drafting of complete rules for sail by Chinese ships from the 
Ussuri river into the Amur river and back. 
  As the commander of Naval Forces of the Russian Border 
Troops, Vice-Admiral Nikolay Kudinov has told INTERFAX, the 
issue on navigation on the Amur and Ussuri rivers will be 
discussed during a visit to China by Russia's Premier Viktor 
Chernomyrdin. 
  Last year's bilateral talks on the issue ended inclusively 
[as received]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

