<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Transfer of River Islands to China Refuted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Transfer of River Islands to China Refuted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2605142194 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 26 May 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> PM2605142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Valeriy Golovin report under the "Talks" rubric: "The </F>
Foreign Ministry Is Authorized To State..."] 
  [Text] Khabarovsk -- "The misgivings of people in the Far 
East about the possible transfer to the PRC of two large islands 
in the Amur River near Khabarovsk are absolutely groundless. 
According to all the realities of history, they belong to 
Russia. I am sure that in time the Chinese side will come to 
accept our logic and our arguments," Genrikh Kireyev, Russian 
Foreign Ministry special envoy and chairman of the Russian 
delegation at the border talks in China, stated at a press 
conference in Khabarovsk. 
  The Russian diplomat was meeting with journalists from 
central and local newspapers after the latest working meeting of 
the members of the Russian-Chinese joint demarcation commission 
had ended in this city. G. Kireyev also refuted rumors that 
2,000 islands will be transferred to the neighboring country 
during the demarcation process. In all there are 1,845 islands 
in the border rivers -- the Ussuri, the Amur, and the Argun. 
Legally speaking, they have never belonged to anyone. The 
demarcation will make it possible to remove that contradiction 
for the first time. Bearing in mind that the border line runs 
along the fairway of the navigable rivers, it may be presumed 
that one-half of the islands will be deemed Russian, the other 
half Chinese. 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman did not agree that 
there is no single approach at government level to the 
assessment of the border problem in the east of the country. 
The members of the Russian delegation at the talks have a 
single directive -- to uphold Russia's interests above all, he 
stressed. 
  However, the participants in the press conference still had 
some uncertainty over the unhindered passage of Chinese ships, 
including naval ones, along the fairway of the Amur River near 
Khabarovsk. This is indeed envisaged by the border settlement 
agreement between Russia and the PRC of 18 May 1991, which 
finally enabled the demarcation work to begin. That agreement 
says that special rules for such traffic must be devised. But 
this has not been done yet. Meanwhile, ships from the PRC sail 
here freely, often without even notifying the Russian side. 
This is causing a negative reaction from the local authorities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

