<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegations To Work 10-12 Days on Fleet Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegations To Work 10-12 Days on Fleet Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605164694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1545 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov and Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] Three-day talks between the Ukrainian and Russian 
government delegations in Moscow on division of the Black Sea 
Fleet ended without result. 
  Vice-Premier Valeriy Shmarov told journalists that the sides 
took "time out of 10-12 days" after which an agreement on the 
first state of the Black Sea Fleet's division may be signed "on 
the basis of almost prepared text of the document." 
  He noted that despite efforts of both delegations "which 
worked for three days in two shifts," work has not been 
completed because every "subject of the division required great 
attention." Shmarov pointed out that the delegations of Russia 
and Ukraine "were on the verge of the document's readiness," 
however "some technical details had to be specified." 
  In the opinion of a member of the Ukrainian delegation, 
Deputy Foreign Minister Boris Tarasyuk, the final document was 
not signed at the talks "not at the fault" of Kiev. He believes 
that the Ukrainian delegation "showed enough flexibility and 
readiness for compromise." Tarasyuk said that the Ukrainian 
side offered during the talks five various drafts agreement. 
  At the same time he believes that the Moscow talks allows to 
speak about "burgeoning breakthrough," which "justifies the 
delay with the signing of the document." 
  Tarasyuk hopes that within 10 days Ukraine and Russia will 
manage at the level of experts to specify and coordinate 
conditions of the division of the Black Sea Fleet and the 
Russian Naval bases in Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

