<H3> <TI>   Dubinin Says Talks With Ukraine Not Useless </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dubinin Says Talks With Ukraine Not Useless </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605150794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1339 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature] </F>
  [Text] Yuriy Dubinin, who led the Russian delegation at the 
recent talks with Ukraine, has no doubt that the issues 
connected with dividing the Black Sea Fleet which remain 
unresolved "will necessarily be thrashed out." 
  As he told INTERFAX on Thursday, the talks between the 
Russian prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, and his Ukrainian 
counterpart, Yukhym Zvyahilskyy, held in Moscow recently "cannot 
be qualified as useless." "The premiers and the two 
delegations did a lot of work and resolved virtually all the 
questions relating to the implementation of instructions issued 
by the presidents of Russia and Ukraine on April 15. A 
resolution has been drafted. There are only a few elements that 
need to be additionally studied and settled," he said. 
  The diplomat refrained from divulging the essence of the 
"elements that still need to be settled" and the agreements 
already reached. "We agreed with our Ukrainian partners that 
none of us will reveal the details of our future accords or 
allow `leakages'," he said. 
  Nevertheless Dubinin said that only a few issues remain to 
be 
settled. 10 to 12 days were allotted for this, he confirmed. 
"We hope that after that an agreement will be signed," he noted. 
  According to Dubinin, the proposed agreement will be signed 
by the two countries' prime ministers. "This might take place in 
Moscow. After all the site of the next meeting is not of 
paramount importance," he said. 
  When asked whether the latest frictions between Ukraine and 
the Crimea were under discussion in Moscow, Dubinin said: "I 
heard not a single word about those problems." 

</TEXT>

