<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Black Sea Navy Regrets Kiev's Inflexibility </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Black Sea Navy Regrets Kiev's Inflexibility </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605141094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1046 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Black Sea Navy Command regrets that the 
negotiations between Russian and Ukrainian Prime Ministers in 
Moscow ended inconclusively. A senior naval officer has told 
Interfax that the Ukrainian side did not display enough 
flexibility over the issue on separate naval bases for Russia 
and Ukraine. 
  In his opinion, the Russian negotiating team accepted a 
tough 
compromise, that was not simple to do, as it offered Kiev to 
deploy Ukrainian ships close to the key Balaklava base near 
Sevastopol. The officer disclosed that the area is the chief 
submarine base for the Black Sea Fleet. 
  "If the Ukrainian delegation accepted the proposal, the 
naval 
command would confront the problem of submarines' redeployment. 
But Kiev ignored even such an offer by Moscow," the officer 
said. 
  In his opinion, the only reason for Kiev's intransigence is 
the lack of funds to modernize wharfs, build headquarters, and 
develop an infrastructure at a new place. 
  Meanwhile, he recalled that the Black Sea Navy Command had 
already cut electricity supply to some Ukrainian army units. 
  "If Kiev fails to pay off the debts, the command reserves 
the 
right to apply similar sanctions to other Ukrainian military 
units," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

