<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Panamanian Foreign Minister on Improving Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Panamanian Foreign Minister on Improving Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705102194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0847 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705102194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Chernov] </F>
  [Text] Panama May 27 TASS -- Relations between Panama and 
Russia must be intensified and expanded, according to Panamanian 
Foreign Minister Gabriel Galindo. He said in an exclusive 
interview with ITAR-TASS that "we are aware of the fact that 
there is much to be done to take relations between Panama and 
one of the world's great powers, Russia, to a level which both 
countries find satisfactory. Nonetheless we can state with 
satisfaction now that a groundwork has been laid for the 
development of mutually beneficial cooperation. The Panamanian 
foreign ministries of Panama and Russia [as received] has made 
steps lately which led to an exchange of consulates general. We 
regard this as a good beginning". 
  According to the Panamanian minister, Russia can use Panama 
as a "gateway for penetrating Latin America". These gateways 
can provide an opportunity for the supply of Russian 
technologies to the countries on that continent and exports of 
manufactured goods, equipment and raw materials. "We would like 
Russia to be a partner capable of making a better use of our 
services, which are undoubtedly the most effective in the 
region". 
  "The liberalization of the Russian economy enables 
Panamanian 
investors to consider seriously prospects for the participation 
in joint ventures on Russian territory. Our diplomats in Moscow 
will be entrusted with bringing home to the Russians what 
advantages cooperation with us can give your entrepreneurs. A 
case in point is the opening of a Russian bank in our 
international financial centre," the minister said. 
  The Union of Banana-Exporting Countries with its 
headquarters 
in Panama, is now studying the possibility of exports to Russia 
and Eastern Europe as a whole, an area which has a huge and 
promising market, the minister said. 
  Gabriel Galindo is a member of the government which is being 
formed by president Ernesto Perez Balladares who won the 
country's general elections on May 8. The new government will 
take office on September 1. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

