<H3> <TI>   Duma Fails To Approve Constitutional Court Candidates </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Fails To Approve Constitutional Court Candidates </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605162394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1046 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] None of the five candidates to sit on the 
Constitutional Court, nominated by Duma factions, collected the 
required majority of votes (225) in a vote in the parliament's 
lower house on Wednesday. 
  Lawyer Oleg Mironov from the Russian Communist Party's 
faction fared best of all with over 41 percent of the votes. 
  As the Duma Legislative Committee's Chairman Vladimir Isakov 
has reported, factions are entitled to put forward their own 
candidates to the president. 
  When a Constitutional Court bill was debated, the lower 
house 
insisted on its right to put forward its candidates to that 
judicial body and amended the law's wording appropriately. 
  In keeping with Russia's Constitution, the president is to 
make the final selection of candidates to sit on the 
Constitutional Court and the Federation Council is to appoint 
them. 
  The Constitutional Court is made up of 19 judges, 6 posts in 
it are currently vacant. 

</TEXT>

