<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Approves First Part of Civil Code </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Approves First Part of Civil Code </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605153294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1143 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 26 TASS -- The lower chamber of the 
Russian federal legislature, the State Duma, approved today what 
Justice Minister Yuriy Kalmykov described as "a document of 
prime importance," the first part of the Civil Code of the 
Russian Federation designed to regulate the most important 
public relations during the country's transition to a market 
economy. 
  The vote was practically unanimous, a rare case in the Duma, 
even though it was preceded by a heated debate. Many speakers 
still remember too well the Soviet Civil Code adopted 30 years 
ago. Common sense prevailed eventually and the chamber approved 
the document after the Agrarian Faction insisted on a 
significant amendment. 
  In preparing the document for second reading, the drafters 
were instructed to proceed from the assumption that the 
alienation and use of land and other natural resources is 
regulated by civil legislation in as much as land and other 
natural resources can be an object of civil turnover under land, 
agrarian and other legislation concerning natural resources. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

