<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ingushetia To Impose Partial State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ingushetia To Impose Partial State of Emergency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605181894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1606 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605181894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Head of the temporary administration in the zone of 
the Ossetian-Ingush conflict Vladimir Lozovoy said that the 
state of emergency will be imposed only on a small part of the 
Sunzhenskiy and Malgobekskiy regions of Ingushetia. 
  Asked by IF's correspondent about the possibility of 
excluding this provision from a draft decree on extension of the 
state of emergency in the conflict zone, Lozovoy said: "I do not 
know why this question arises. We agreed on it with the Ingush 
president and he had no objections to it." 
  "These parts of the Sunzhenskiy and Malgobekskiy regions 
will 
perform the role of a buffer zone to prevent penetration of 
militants in the zone of the Ossetian-Ingush conflict," Lozovoy 
said. 
  In the meantime, in neighboring Chechnya armed forces were 
put on alert in connection with the possible expansion of the 
state of emergency in the zone of the Ossetian-Ingush conflict. 
  Groznyy assessed the intention to include the Sunzhenskiy 
and 
Malgobekskiy regions of Ingushetia in the state of emergency 
zone as "an act of open armed aggression." With the lack of an 
administrative border between Chechnya and Ingushetia these 
regions are a subject of dispute between the two republics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64025 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov103_d_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-103 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

