<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice President on State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice President on State of Emergency </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605174194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1706 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605174194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The draft decree on expansion of the zone of state 
of emergency to the Ingush regions of Sunzhen and Malgobek is 
needed for settlement of the problem with Chechnya by force, 
Ingush Vice President Boris Agapov suggested. He stressed in an 
interview with Interfax that such "unreasonable decrees seem to 
be needed in order to lay the Russian president open to a blow." 
  Agapov said there was an evident attempt to create 
confrontation between the president and the Federation Council 
which would have to adopt the draft decree on May 31 when the 
term for the state of emergency expired. 
  Agapov emphasized that the process of territorial division 
between Chechnya and Ingushetia concerned these two regions 
which were disputed areas. 
  The decree said that the populated centers which, as 
Ingushetia had agreed, would go to the Chechen Republic of 
Ichkeria, would be included in the zone of the state of 
emergency, Agapov pointed out. 
  In the context of this situation inclusion of the Sunzhen 
and 
Malgobek regions into the state of emergency zone would mean a 
seizure of Chechen territory. It is hard even to imagine all 
consequences of such a move, Agapov underlined. 
  Agapov disapproved of this decision. He announced that when 
he had told the interim administration about it the 
administration had responded that it never knew about such 
serious consequences. 
  Agapov suggested that such recommendations could have been 
given by some politicians from the center who occupied certain 
posts in the federal bodies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

