<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   State of Emergency Termed `Aggression' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State of Emergency Termed `Aggression' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2705085794 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 27 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK2705085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Natalya Gorodetskaya report in the "Caucasus" column: </F>
"Chechnya's Army Has Been Put on Alert. The Republic Is Ready 
To Resist the Expansion of the State of Emergency Zone in 
Ingushetia"] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Federation Council Deputy 
Valeriy Fateyev, who recently visited the zone of the 
Ossetian-Ingush conflict, stated that the draft edict on 
extending the state of emergency in its present shape must not 
be signed under any circumstances. According to the deputy, it 
is important to "neutralize" the influence of politicians who 
"draft such edicts" and furthermore understand why they do this, 
he stressed. Mr. Fateyev said that such an approach contradicts 
the interests of the peoples of Russia and the North Caucasus 
because it will undoubtedly evoke a negative reaction from 
Chechnya and Ingushetia, which will aggravate the situation even 
more. 
  The Chechen Republic of Ichkeria has already responded to 
the 
proposed option for stabilizing the situation in the emergency 
zone. Groznyy's official statement disseminated yesterday says 
that "the attempt to spread the emergency regime in the zone of 
the Ossetian-Ingush conflict to these areas will be seen by 
Chechnya as an act of open armed aggression." "The Chechen 
Foreign Ministry regards this as interference in the republic's 
internal affairs and in the event that Russian troops are 
positioned here, will view this as armed aggression," Chechnya's 
Foreign Minister Shamseddin Yusef stated in an interview with 
INTERFAX. According to him, in this event the republic will 
reserve the right to curb invasion of its territory by a foreign 
army. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

