<H3> <TI>   Dniester Leader Says Russia Applying Economic Pressure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dniester Leader Says Russia Applying Economic Pressure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505164394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1345 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505164394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Valeriy Demidetskiy and </F>
Anatoliy Kholoyuk] 
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau] May 25 TASS -- Igor Smirnov, 
leader of the split-way Dniester Republic, today accused 
"definite political circles in Russia and Moldova of 
economically blackmailing the Dniester Republic". 
  Addressing a session of the Supreme Soviet of his 
unrecognised republic, he claimed that the said forces were 
"deliberately destabilising the financial situation on the 
left-hand bank of the Dniester River, striving to make Tiraspol 
more tractable in the talks on the withdrawal of the Russian 
14th Army and on problems linked with its property". 
  The Dniester parliament today discussed the acute money 
shortage in the region. Tiraspol had refused to use Moldovan 
leis on its territory and decided to leave in circulation the 
Soviet money, annulled in all the CIS republics. This resulted 
in the catastrophic destabilisation of the financial system and 
led to the growth of inflation. 
  "The 60 billion roubles now in circulation are not enough to 
meet current expenses," Chairman of the Dniester Bank Vyacheslav 
Zagryadskiy told the parliament. He said that the government 
should deliver to Tiraspol the new money printed in Russia for 
the Dniester region. But "this cannot be done now due to the 
ban imposed by the Russian leadership," he noted. 
  The Dniester parliament decided to address an appeal to the 
Russian president, the State Duma and the Council of the 
Federation, asking them to help the Dniester administration 
solve the problem of cash money. 

</TEXT>

