<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Russia, Ukraine Should Avoid Media War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Says Russia, Ukraine Should Avoid Media War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605214794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2031 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605214794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent Yuriy Sizov] </F>
  [Text] Kiev May 26 TASS -- "We should take joint efforts to 
avoid media confrontation. This can be achieved mostly by means 
of consultations, negotiations and compromises", Ukraine 
president's spokesman Viktor Stelmakh said in an exclusive 
interview with TASS on Thursday. 
  Commenting on the decision by Ukraine's Foreign Ministry to 
strip three newsmen of the Ostankino TV network of their 
accreditation and on the protest of Russian media chiefs against 
this decision, the spokesman noted that recently Ukraine had 
become "an objective of a massed information onslaught by 
Russian and some foreign mass media", adding that "for some 
objective reasons, our information capacities cannot be 
considered adequate". 
  "Perhaps this prompted the Ukrainian Foreign Ministry to 
resort to such a drastic measure as a means of self-defence", he 
explained. 
  According to Stelmakh, Ukraine is also concerned over 
certain 
statements by Russian top officials, which he described as "far 
from being friendly", which cannot but affect relations between 
the two countries. 
  The spokesman expressed confidence that there would not be 
any reasons for "raising a question about violation of 
international law with respect to media representatives" if the 
two states carry on a constructive dialogue for better mutual 
understanding and if newsmen comply with rules of journalists' 
ethics. 
  Stelmakh dismissed recent reports about the possibility of 
discriminatory measures towards TASS correspondents in Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64036 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov103_e_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-103 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tarasyuk: Ukraine `Not To Blame' for Failure To Sign Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tarasyuk: Ukraine `Not To Blame' for Failure To Sign Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605142094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1046 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605142094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] "The Ukrainian side is not to blame" for failure to 
sign the final document on the Black Sea Fleet's division at the 
Ukrainian-Russian negotiations, the Ukrainian chief negotiator 
Boris Tarasyuk, a deputy foreign minister has told journalists 
on his return from Moscow. 
  In his opinion, the Ukrainian delegation "displayed enough 
flexibility and readiness to compromise." The Ukrainian side, 
he noted, offered five draft accords to choose from. 
  At the same time, Tarasyuk described the latest round of 
talks in Moscow as "very useful." "The shaping-up breakthrough 
justifies the delay with signing a document," he said. 
  In his words, Ukrainian and Russian experts are given ten 
days to agree on terms to divide the Black Sea Fleet and to set 
aside bases for the Russian Navy in Ukraine. 
  He reported that the negotiation partners had reaffirmed the 
outcome of the previous talks on the Black Sea Fleet's division 
and "agreed approaches to the crucial issues" on Russian naval 
facilities. 
  At the same, in his words, "one cannot talk of the complete 
absence of differences, which is natural since the interests of 
the two states are at stake." 

</TEXT>

