<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Situation Calm While Crimean Parliament Meets </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Situation Calm While Crimean Parliament Meets </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605153194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1425 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Karmalito] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol May 26 TASS -- The Crimean local 
parliament's first session resumed its work on Thursday by 
electing Crimean representatives to a joint working group, which 
is to prepare agreed-upon proposals for the Ukrainian and 
Crimean parliaments. 
  The working group is being set up under a decision taken as 
a 
result of the Kiev talks earlier this week between Ukrainian and 
Crimean plenipotentiary parliamentary delegations. The group 
will include five Crimean lawmakers, as well as four experts in 
law. 
  At the same time, the Crimean parliamentarians postponed at 
least until tomorrow debates on the issue of suspending, for the 
period of the group's activities, the acts passed by parliament 
on May 20, 1994. 
  The session, which ajourned last week after passing a law 
"On 
Restoration of Consitutional Foundations of the Crimean 
Republic's Statehood", is due to approve a new Crimean 
Government named by President Yuriy Meshkov. Lawmakers will 
also discuss a programme for pulling the peninsula out of the 
current economic crisis and for stabilizing its agro-industrial 
complex, as well as endorse a series of presidential decrees. 
  The session is proceeding in a quiet and businesslike 
atmosphere. Passions outside the parliament building calmed 
down. A mere several dozens of demonstrators still go on 
picketing under slogans demanding for greater independence for 
the Crimean republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

