<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moroz Suspended as Socialist Party Leader </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moroz Suspended as Socialist Party Leader </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2605145794 Kiev KIYEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI in Russian 25 May 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> WS2605145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev KIYEVSKIYE VEDOMOSTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Oleksandr Moroz Suspended As </F>
Ukrainian Socialist Party Leader"] 
  [Text] On 21 May, the Ukrainian Socialist Party [SPU] 
Political Council held a meeting. The SPU leadership met 
Oleksandr Morozov's request and decided to suspend his powers as 
the party's leader. According to a declaration issued by the 
Political Council, this was a justified move: The Supreme 
Council chairman is not allowed to pursue internal party 
interests (which are many) to the detriment of national 
interests (which are even more). On the other hand, the 
document's authors said that Oleksandr Moroz will remain 
unquestioned leader of the party. Sergey Kishko, people's deputy 
and assistant professor at the Donetsk State Technical 
University, was appointed acting head of the organization. 
According to its statute, the issue of the party's chairman 
will be examined at its congress set for this fall. Curiously 
enough, Oleksandr Moroz did not attend the meeting since he went 
to Kanev to participate in festivities devoted to the reburial 
of Taras Shevchenko's remains. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

