<H3> <TI>   Fuel-Starved Nuclear Plants in Danger of Closure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fuel-Starved Nuclear Plants in Danger of Closure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605175194 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1300 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2605175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] If power engineering stops, all other industries 
will stop. This was what Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk 
told a conference of electric power engineering enterprises' 
managers. Conditions are rife for this. The situation that has 
come about in this basic industry of exceptional significance to 
the national economy, is extremely complex and serious. There 
are, in particular, quite a lot of problems in nuclear power 
engineering that, to a considerable extent, ensured the work of 
the national economic complex last winter. 
  Even now we are fulfilling our commitments to the state and 
increasing the output of the cheapest kind of electric power, 
said Mykhaylo Umanets, Ukraine's DerzhKomAtom [State Committee 
for the Use of Nuclear Power] chairman. All our reserves have 
unfortunately been extended. Some of the generating sets have 
not been provided with fuel and will stop in the very near 
future. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

