<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Addresses Counterintelligence Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Addresses Counterintelligence Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Submits Counterintelligence Bill </H4>

<F P=102> LD2705110194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1033 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By CRIME-TASS correspondent Olga Semionova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 27 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin told the collegium of the Federal Counterintelligence 
Service (FCIS) on Thursday that he had sent to the State Duma 
for approval the law on the Federal Counterintelligence Service 
after endorsing it, the FCIS chief, Sergey Stepashin announced 
at the continuing conference of the service leaders. 
  The passing of the law will strengthen the legal framework 
which is now operating on the basis of the regulation signed by 
the president in January. 
  While in the FCIS, Yeltsin proposed to restore the 
investigative department to the service, which had been taken 
away from it after the president had signed a decree in December 
ordering the reorganization of the security agencies of the 
Russian Federation. It has become clear since that time that the 
move complicated the activity of the FCIS, as well as of the 
prosecutor's office and the interior affairs agencies. They had 
to investigate cases for which they had no adequate experience 
and lacked appropriate support. 

</TEXT>

