<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Map Declassification Gathers Pace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Map Declassification Gathers Pace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605111894 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1000 GMT 
25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2605111894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The discussion and, especially, the revision of 
borders has always been a fraught business, so to speak, even if 
it only takes place on paper. Participants in an international 
conference on cartography which opened in Moscow today know this 
well. Over to our correspondent, Andrey Zenkov: 
  [Zenkov] In various eras, no matter how different the 
prevailing social system, no matter how complex the internal and 
external political situation, the Geographical Department, the 
Maps Department, the Supreme Geodesic Directorate, the Main 
Directorate for Cartography attached to the Council of Ministers 
and, now, Russia's Federal Service for Geodesy and Cartography, 
have always done basically the same job. With assistance from 
their experts they entered on maps the dividing lines which 
politicians, assisted by the military, decided on. For 68 years 
of its 75-year existence the Russian cartographic service has 
answered to the KGB, the Ministry of Internal Affairs, the State 
Committee for Construction, the Ministry of Ecology, or the 
Ministry of Natural Resources. Each of these bodies had its own 
priorities. 
  [Begin Zhalkovskiy recording] We have now managed to 
declassify maps in the 1:1,000,000 series, the 1:500,000 series, 
and the 1:200,000 series. The Ministry of Defense has also 
agreed to the declassification of the 1:100,000 series. Maps 
for the use of the public, including maps of oblasts, maps of 
rayons, and maps of regions, are being produced on the basis of 
these maps. We will produce these maps. In fact we have 
already started. They will be very detailed. You will be able 
to find your own village -- and maybe even your own house on 
them. [end recording] 
  As Yevgeniy Zhalkovskiy, first deputy head of the service, 
told me, few people realize that throughout the entire existence 
of the USSR, the only countries with whom we had official 
agreements on the mapping of borders were Finland, Poland, 
Korea, and Mongolia. Today special commissions are discussing 
these extremely difficult issues with the Baltic republics and 
the countries of the Caucasus region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

