<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investigation Into Oct Uprising Faulty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Investigation Into Oct Uprising Faulty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605153994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1046 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Investigators into last October's parliamentary 
uprising made serious mistakes, a commission of the Prosecutor 
General's Office concluded. This is precisely why Deputy 
Prosecutor General Vladimir Kravtsev was dismissed. 
  Although the formula of indictment on former Vice President 
Aleksandr Rutskoy, ex-Speaker Ruslan Khasbulatov and former 
Deputy Soviet Defence Minister Vladislav Achalov was ready in 
January, this was delayed because of incomplete work on 
plaintiffs and damage sustained. Other mistakes include lack of 
coordination and duplication of work by separate investigating 
teams. The files were kept apart and none of the teams had 
enough information to substantiate the case. 
  The commission also indicated that a substantial part of 
external investigating officers had little experience with 28 
percent of prosecuting officers and 33 percent of police 
investigators having work records of less than three years. As 
many as 7,000 witnesses had been questioned and the identity 
established of 151 dead victims and 913 wounded casualties by 
February 22 when the State Duma declared an amnesty. 
  Apart from subjective reasons, the investigation was also 
hampered because of delays caused by a number of government 
bodies. Despite the PGO's [Prosecutor General's Office] repeated 
requests, no estimates were provided of the damage done to the 
buildings of the Russian parliament and Moscow mayor's office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

