<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Creates Own TV, Radio Service </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Duma Creates Own TV, Radio Service </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705095894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0758 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705095894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 27 TASS -- The Russian State Duma Snubbed 
President Boris Yeltsin on Friday by deciding to create its own 
TV and radio service. 
  On Thursday Presidential Spokesman Vyacheslav Kostikov urged 
the lower chamber on behalf of the Russian President to refrain 
from such a decision, but the request was ignored. 
  The TV and radio service will employ 49 people and is to 
daily report on activities of legislative authorities. 
Representatives of various factions will have 30 minutes of 
daily air time. 
  The Duma thus followed suit of the former Russian 
legislature, the Supreme Soviet, which was dissolved by the 
President last September. It had also created its own TV 
service which appeared on central TV with the "parliamentary 
hour" programme. The broadcasts were intended to provide 
objective coverage of the work of the legislature which said 
that state-controlled media was biased about it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

