<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filatov Previews Forthcoming Economic Edicts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Filatov Previews Forthcoming Economic Edicts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605193894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1547 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 26 TASS -- Following this week's package 
of decrees aiming to speed economic reforms, Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin is now preparing another series of decrees to 
regulate the sphere of production, according to Sergey Filatov, 
chief of the presidential staff. 
  Addressing participants in a regular ceremony of signing the 
treaty of social accord in the Grand Kremlin Palace, Filatov 
said the package of decress now under preparation is above all 
aims to improve efficiency of tax offices. "The poor performance 
of tax services results in such losses that their reducing by 
20-30 per cent would enable to cover the entire federal budget 
deficit", he noted. 
  The chief of the presidential staff listed priorities to be 
addressed by the said decrees. They include cutbacks in state 
subsidies and preferential support of enterprises, protection of 
private ownership, encouragement of private and foreign 
investments. 
  The president also intends to issue an order on division 
between the economic and social activities of enterprises with a 
view to put an end to what head of the group of experts under 
the Russian president, Aleksandr Lifshits, described as "factory 
socialism". 
  Some measures are also expected to be taken for equitable 
distribution of reform burden among all sections of the 
population. 
  Filatov stressed that time had come to pass from words about 
reform to the reform itself, which the old parliament failed to 
do, despite repeated and urgent appeals by President Yeltsin. 

</TEXT>

