<H3> <TI>   Deputies' Failure To Explain Reform Criticized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputies' Failure To Explain Reform Criticized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605111994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1033 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 26 TASS -- First Vice-Premier Oleg 
Soskovets opened a regular session of the Russian Government 
today, criticising Russian ministers for inadequate activities 
in bringing home to the people the importance of Russian 
president's decrees on boosting economic reform. Soskovets 
described the government' activities in this field as "obviously 
insufficient." 
  A package of documents on the reform of state-run 
enterprises, strengthening taxation policies, streamlining 
payments and abolishing export quotas and licenses was prepared 
by the Russian Government and signed by the president on May 23. 
  "Despite an avalanche of comments on the latest presidential 
decrees, the Russian ministers's voice is almost inaudible," 
Soskovets said. "It is the cabinet which should be the first to 
analyse laws which the ministers will have to comply with, bring 
them home to the people and make their forecasts," Soskovets 
said. 
  On his initiative the government adopted a resolution to 
establish control over the implementation of the president's 
decrees on stepping up the economic reform. Under the 
resolution, heads of federal and regional executive bodies were 
instructed to hold conferences and seminars to discuss recent 
presidential decrees, inviting managers of enterprises to attend. 

</TEXT>

