<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Majority Polled Report Drop in Living Standards </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Majority Polled Report Drop in Living Standards </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605142794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1201 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 26 TASS -- The results of a public 
opinion poll conducted by the "Mnenie" sociological service 
showed that every second respondent considers the financial 
status of his family to be not very good. A total of 17 per 
cent of respondents said they can hardly make both ends meet, 
while only three per cent are quite satisfied with their incomes 
and 27 per cent admitted that their incomes are relatively not 
bad. 
  The majority of these polled (65 per cent) said that five 
years ago they lived much better. A total of 22 per cent said 
that their incomes had grown, while 11 per cent believe that 
their incomes remained at about the same level. 
  Almost half of respondents (47 per cent) resolutely declined 
to make any forecasts about their future incomes. The number of 
optimists hoping that in five years their life will change for 
the better makes up about 27 per cent, with 6 per cent 
cherishing hopes of getting rich. However, 13 per cent cherish 
no such hopes and are preparing to tighten their belts. 
  Taking part in the poll were 3,535 respondents from 190 
Russian settlements located in 30 regions of the Russian 
Federation. 

</TEXT>

