<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Rejects Draft Investment Program </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Rejects Draft Investment Program </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605125494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1106 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 26 TASS -- During its meeting on 
Thursday, the Russian Federal Government rejected the draft of 
the federal investment programme for 1994 which had been 
submitted by the Finance Ministry. The rejection was largely 
inspired by the draft's lack of a mechanism for creating an 
investment market in the country. The Finance Ministry has been 
given a week to resubmit an improved draft programme. 
  Investment in Russia continued to decline in 1993, due to 
the 
overall fall in production, high inflation rates, and the high 
risk level for private investors. Despite the government's 
efforts to stimulate investment by cancelling the tax on profits 
which are reinvested, offering subsidized credits, and 
reassessing basic assets, the rate of decline was only slowed 
somewhat. In 1993, the value of investments declined by 16 per 
cent, compared to 40 per cent in 1992, according to the report 
presented to the government today by First Deputy Finance 
Minister Yakov Urinson. 
  Urinson pointed out two priorities for the government 
investment policy. The first is the more effective use of 
investments provided by the state budget, with a transition away 
from credits "on demand" towards those given out only to the 
most promising enterprises after examining their business plans. 
  The second priority stresses the formation of a more 
attractive investment climate drawing on funds from enterprises 
themselves and private investors. 
  The Finance Ministry feels that the implementation of those 
measures will improve the investment climate already in 1994, 
and have its greatest effect in 1995. However, Urinson pointed 
out, overall investments from all sources into the country's 
economy have declined by 10 per cent in 1994. Government 
centralized investments have gone down by 40 per cent. The 
remaining funds will be directed towards easing the most serious 
problems. 
  The draft presented by the Finance Ministry included the 
suggestions of many ministries and departments. In particular, 
the state construction committee suggested that a point be added 
to the draft about opening special accounts for amortization 
deductions and advancing up to 30 per cent of the yearly limit 
to companies working on contract. The Russian Agricultural 
Ministry protested that the draft did not envisage the financing 
of branches of the agro-industrial complex from the federal 
budget, whose funds are handed out only for the support of the 
most important sectors of the economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64085 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov103_b_94032" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-103 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

