<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Chief Said To Oppose Economic Edicts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central Bank Chief Said To Oppose Economic Edicts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605141194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1046 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At its Thursday's session the Russian Government 
decided to organize control over the implementation of the 
package of economic decrees signed by President Yeltsin recently. 
  Addressing the session, First Deputy Premier Oleg Soskovets 
stressed that real life in Russia "overtakes the processes of 
law-making," and that the "package of presidential economic 
decrees" is designed to "resolve problems that piled up largely 
in the area of finances and material production skillfully and 
gradually." 
  According to Soskovets, the "essence and the content" of 
Boris Yeltsin's decrees connected with reforming state-owned 
enterprises, taxation policy, quotas and other issues "pursue 
only one goal -- to put the country's economy in order." 
  "Many provisions in the package of the president's decrees 
conflict with the present legislation, and some of them give 
rise to amazement," countered the chairman of Russia's Central 
Bank, Viktor Gerashchenko. He called for convening a special 
government session to analyse and discuss the decrees. 
  However Gerashchenko's call failed to find support, and 
participants in the government session approved the draft 
resolution which contains a system of concrete measures designed 
to monitor the implementation of presidential decrees. 

</TEXT>

