<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Deputy Against Experimenting With Army </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Deputy Against Experimenting With Army </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605163194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1239 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 26 TASS -- "The Army must not be 
subjected to any experiments. We must not save or make money on 
the defenders of our homeland," Air Major-General Nikolay 
Bezborodov, vice-chairman of the Duma Defence Committee, told 
ITAR-TASS today. He noted that trips of MPs to garrisons of the 
Far Eastern Military Area and to the Northern Fleet have 
confirmed that minimum funds, sufficient only for every-day 
needs, are being allocated to the military establishment. This 
calls in question the proper organisation of military training 
and the protection of Russia's interests and security. 
  The materials of the investigation, Bezborodov said, have 
been submitted to the Defence Council of the State Duma, to the 
government, and to the president of the Russian Federation. The 
committee is sure that it is necessary to radically revise the 
financing of the Armed Forces. The situation when servicemen 
and the civilian personnel are not paid their salaries for 2-3 
months running can by no means be regarded as normal. This 
creates a tense situation in some garrisons, where the families 
of servicemen live only on Army cash allowances. 
  Bezborodov said that the president's stand on the military 
budget was clear. He wants minimum funds to be allocated, which 
would keep the combat readiness of the Armed Forces at the 
needed level, would ensure the survival of the military science 
and purchases of the needed armaments. The president is sure 
that this is the duty of the state. 
  "The privileges accorded to servicemen should neither be 
expanded nor curtailed," the vice-chairman of the Duma Defence 
Committee stressed. Reports have appeared that the Russian 
Government was allegedly proposing to pay minimum compensation 
for the present food rations. Defence Ministry experts have 
made corresponding calculations, which showed that in this case 
all the servicemen would prefer to get food rations instead of 
money. This will be much more expensive to the state. "The 
committee will approach these problems most seriously," the 
general stated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

