<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Union Demands More Money To Treat Chernobyl Victims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Union Demands More Money To Treat Chernobyl Victims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2705085194 Minsk BELAPAN in Belarusian 1600 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2705085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk BELAPAN </F>
<F P=105>  Belarusian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "The Presidium of the Belarusian </F>
Trade Union Federation Holds Its Session"] 
  [Text] The Presidium of the Belarusian Trade Union 
Federation [FPB] held a session on 26 May at its headquarters. 
BELAPAN has learned that two key issues -- a summer treatment 
program for working people and their children and an increase in 
the minimum wage -- were discussed. In particular, it was 
stated that the government allocated 120 billion rubles [R] to 
treat those who suffered from the Chernobyl tragedy's aftermath. 
However, this money will cover treatment for only 15 percent of 
all those who actually need it. The Gomel Oblast Trade Union 
Council sent an open letter to Belarusian Prime Minister 
Vyachaslaw Kebich presenting the statistics regarding Gomel 
Oblast residents who badly need this treatment. 
  The participants in the FPB session also raised the issue of 
increasing the minimum wage. According to the trilateral 
general agreement -- signed by the government, trade unions, and 
the Association of Employers -- the divergencies between indexes 
of a minimum consumer budget and a minimum wage should not 
exceed 27 percent. According to FPB experts's estimates, the 
minimum consumer budget (in June 1994 prices) will stand at 
R160,000 (currently, it is R60,000). 
  All these issues will be raised at the session of the 
Conciliatory Council of the Republic of Belarus, which includes 
representatives from the government, the FPB, and the 
Association of Employers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

