<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Republic Adopts Money Coupons </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dniester Republic Adopts Money Coupons </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2605121394 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 26 May 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK2605121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "NEGA Reports" rubric] </F>
  [Text] An acute shortage of cash and a big backlog of 
salaries, pensions, benefits, and allowances are forcing the 
Dniester leaders to turn to the Russian Federation Court of 
Arbitration. The ruling it adopted back on 18 January 1993 
found in favor of the action brought by the Dniester Regional 
Bank against the Moscow Goznak printing factory. The latter was 
requested to carry out its obligation to ship the Dniester money 
coupons manufactured by it in accordance with a paid order. 
  The introduction of Dniester money coupons is regarded as a 
temporary and purely economic measure helping to stabilize the 
position with cash until a general agreement with Moldova has 
been reached, Grigoriy Marakutsa, chairman of the Supreme Soviet 
of the unrecognized Dniester Moldovan Republic, explained to a 
NEGA correspondent. Its implementation, however, has been 
stopped by Russia -- not without some pressure from Chisinau 
officials, informed sources say. 
  The 24 May session of the Supreme Soviet of the Dniester 
Moldovan Republic that discussed the debts problem adopted an 
appeal to the Russian president, the Federation Council, and the 
State Duma with a request to positively resolve the question 
decided long ago by the Russian Federation Court of Arbitration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

