<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Marks Independence Day at Military Parade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze Marks Independence Day at Military Parade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605125894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1110 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi May 26 TASS -- Georgian leader Eduard 
Shevardnadze said: "Since Georgia normalised relations with 
Russia, and President Boris Yeltsin and myself announced to the 
world that our countries are friends and good neighbours, it has 
become possible to build the republic's strong armed forces as 
guarantors of Georgia's independence and territorial integrity." 
  The statement, made at the close of the military parade in 
Tbilisi's Central Square to mark independence day, was born out 
by the march-past of infantry, naval and paratrooper units 
sporting new uniforms and armed with the latest Kalashnikov 
automatic guns, the roll-past of armoured vehicles, artillery 
guns and anti-aircraft missiles. A squad of the Su-25 attack 
planes assembled at the Tbilisi plant performed aerobatics in 
the sky above the Central Square during the parade. 

</TEXT>

