<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Says Moscow Talks With Crimea `Ended in a Draw' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Says Moscow Talks With Crimea `Ended in a Draw' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605121794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1111 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By UKRINFORM correspondent Sergey Balykov for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Kiev May 26 TASS -- Ukrainian Acting Prime Minister 
Yukhym Zvyahilskyy believes the talks in Moscow on the Black Sea 
Fleet and the Crimea ended in a draw. "In Moscow we did not 
win, but did not lose either," he told UKRINFORM upon his return 
from the Russian capital. 
  Zvyahilskyy described the talks as "very tense and nervous." 
"We tried to find variants of a positive solution of the tasks 
set by the Ukrainian president. We made concessions, but only 
those which could not result in the loss of Ukrainian wealth, 
its independence and sovereignty," he stressed. 
  The head of government said that five variants of the 
agreement, including that of the president, were submitted for 
Russian consideration. "The fact that none of them was adopted 
does not mean a defeat," he stressed and added that positive 
moments achieved in Moscow would help resume talks "more 
concretely, on the most acute issue." 
  The second round of negotiations is expected to begin in 
Kiev 
in 10-15 days. 
  According to Zvyahilskyy, during the Moscow talks "severe 
fight was going on for each word, for each sentence in the 
document which can help untie the Black Sea knot." He believes 
that the sides succeeded in general to positively solve the 
problem of sharing the disputed navy. Sevastopol will house the 
major base of the Russian Navy, while Balaklava and Donuzlav 
will become the main bases of the Ukrainian fleet, according to 
him. 
  "Donuzlav is a mighty and well-equipped base and Ukraine had 
no serious objections" about it. "Disagreements emerged after 
the Russian side raised the issue of basing its navy in other 
ports," he explained. 
  Zvyahilskyy hopes that the second round of negotiations will 
be "more constructive" and will result in the signing of the 
document on the Black Sea Fleet. 

</TEXT>

