<F P=106> [Konstantin Parishkura report from Kiev under general </F>
headline: "Russia And Ukraine Have Divided the Ships. Now They 
Are Only Left To Decide on How To Position Them"] 
  [Text] On Wednesday Boris Oleynik, chief of the Ukrainian 
parliamentary delegation at the negotiations with the Crimean 
Supreme Council delegation, at a news conference voiced his 
satisfaction with the results of the meeting with delegates from 
the peninsula. As is known, a decision was made to recommend to 
the Ukrainian and Crimean Supreme Councils that they set up a 
joint working group. The Ukrainian delegation asked the Crimean 
Supreme Council within three days to consider the question of 
suspending the legislative acts adopted on 20 May for the entire 
period that the joint working group will be in session. 
  Sergey Tsekov, chairman of the Crimean Supreme Council, 
stated that Crimea has no intention of seceding from Ukraine: 
"This can be suggested only by those who are not familiar with 
the content of Crimean laws." True, he failed to respond to the 
question about how his words correlate with the program 
provision of the Crimean Republican Party, of which he is a 
member, about the peninsula's joining Russia. 

