<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Rescinds Resignation as Vice Premier </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Rescinds Resignation as Vice Premier </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2705104494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1018 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2705104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 27 TASS -- Sergey Shakhray on Friday said 
his resignation as vice-premier is no longer on the agenda. "The 
president did not accept my resignation and I found it incorrect 
to insist further," he said in an interview with ITAR-TASS. 
Shakhray added that republics and other regions within the 
Russian Federation had sent many appeals to the president not to 
accept his resignation. 
  Shakhray said he discussed with President Yeltsin different 
aspects of the regional policy, including the signing of the 
agreement with Kaliningrad, the regulation of relations with the 
Chechen Republic and a mechanism implementing the treaty with 
Tatarstan. 
  Explaining his recent moves, including the announcement of 
his resignation, Shakhray referred to the breach of office 
ethics in dismissing him from the post of the minister of 
nationalities and regional policy. According to Shakhray, "it 
is not ethical to work on the president's team and announce 
one's disagreement with things. I do not want to repeat the 
behavior of some politicians". These were the motives behind 
his announced resignation. 
  As concerns his relations with the newly appointed Minister 
Nikolay Yegorov, Shakhray said he would "help the new minister 
of nationalities and regional policy. I wished him well when 
introducing the man to the ministry collective. Now everything 
will depend on himself". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

