<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Addresses Counterintelligence Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Addresses Counterintelligence Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Warns Organized Crime Seeking Power </H4>

<F P=102> LD2605204094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1758 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605204094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian President Boris Yeltsin expressed extreme 
concern over the criminalization of society. Speaking at the 
All-Russian conference of the Federal Counter-Intelligence 
Service [FCIS] in Moscow on Thursday, he pointed out that 
"violent crimes by organized groups take the form of criminal 
terrorism." 
  In Yeltsin's words, "the corruption of power structures, 
law-enforcement and other state bodies especially in the sphere 
of redistribution of property is extremely dangerous for the 
state." 
  The Russian president noted that "organized crime is already 
not confined to the sphere of regular crimes. It seeks to enter 
big politics, to gain access to ruling the state and its 
regions." 
  The FCIS should prevent such attempts with all of its 
operational and technical potential, Yeltsin said. "In 
interaction with the Interior Ministry and tax police it is 
necessary to reveal criminal sources, the financing of political 
campaigns, ties of state and political figures with organizers 
of criminal gangs which seek to have their people in state 
bodies, and are subsidized from abroad," he pointed out. 
  The president noted that Russia's nuclear safety is an 
extremely important problem. "We should prevent proliferation of 
nuclear and other arms of mass annihilation all over the country 
and abroad," he noted. 
  Yeltsin believes that the counter-intelligence bodies should 
be outside politics. As for its servicemen they cannot combine 
their work with political activities, i.e. to serve the 
interests of a party or a public organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64136 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov103_g_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-103 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Addresses SELSKAYA ZHIZN Readers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Addresses SELSKAYA ZHIZN Readers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2605120594 Moscow SELSKAYA ZHIZN in Russian 26 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2605120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SELSKAYA ZHIZN </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Address from Republic of Belarus Government "To the Readers </F>
of This Issue"] 
  [Text] Esteemed rural workers of the Russian Federation! 
The mutual interest in the lives of our states' peoples is 
determined by the proximity of their destinies in the past and 
present. 
  The Belarusian countryside is experiencing similar 
difficulties to the Russian countryside at a complex period in 
its history. In the recent past Belarus was one of the leading 
republics in terms of per capita agricultural production. 
  The marketable production of milk, meat, and potatoes made 
it 
possible not only to meet our own requirements but also to 
deliver a substantial quantity, under mutually advantageous 
exchange, to other republics and primarily to Russia. Large 
livestock raising complexes similar to the specialized farming 
facilities of Western countries made it possible to achieve high 
production indicators. 
  Belarus was one of the Russian countryside' most reliable 
partners for deliveries of tractors, other agricultural 
equipment, and mineral fertilizers. Today too it is prepared 
for the closest cooperation with Russia's rural workers and to 
supply reliable equipment and other output. The actions of our 
states' governments in concluding the treaty on the union of our 
monetary systems were also aimed at such relations. 
  With the start of the treaty's operation artificial 
obstacles 
will be lifted which are dividing not only states but primarily 
the inhabitants of cities and villages -- barriers which have 
artificially arisen between us. 
  The present development of the Republic of Belarus' 
agriculture is proceeding within the scheme of a mixed economy 
and rational support for collective farms and peasants' private 
plots. The main principle of our reforms in the countryside is 
not to destroy but to help all commodity producers irrespective 
of forms of ownership, all those who are able and capable and 
willing to work honestly on the land. 
  The breakdown of our ties is affecting the position of the 
Belarusian countryside, the production of reliable agricultural 
equipment, and the mutually advantageous exchange of the fruit 
of their labor between the peoples of Russia and Belarus. 
  We sincerely hope that this influence is of a temporary, 
transient nature and that common sense will prevail. 
  We wish that the Russian rural workers may successfully 
overcome the difficulties of our complex time and we wish them 
favorable conditions for spring work and hope for the 
restoration and development of the traditional fraternal ties 
with the Belarusian countryside and between our peoples. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64137 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov103_r_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-103 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Azebaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armenia, Azerbaijan Violate Karabakh Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Armenia, Azerbaijan Violate Karabakh Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605132294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1046 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2605132294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Armenian and Azerbaijani formations operating in 
the zone of the Karabakh conflict have violated the cease-fire 
agreement on several occasions, although the general situation 
is relatively calm. 
  According to a well-informed source in the Azerbaijani 
Defense Ministry, Karabakh soldiers fired at the Azerbaijani 
positions in the Fizuli, Geranboy and Agdam regions. 
  The same source reports that a number of villages in 
Azerbaijan's Tauz and Kedabek border regions were shelled from 
Armenia and that personnel and equipment were transferred from 
Armenia to Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  Meanwhile, the Karabakh Defense Ministry's press service 
reports that Azerbaijani units shelled Karabakh positions in the 
Agdam direction last night. No return fire was opened. 

</TEXT>

