<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interstate Space Committee Plans New Cooperation Program </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Interstate Space Committee Plans New Cooperation Program </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005152794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1252 GMT 30 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3005152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Interstate Space Committee uniting the former 
Soviet republics, except the Baltic countries and Georgia, is to 
adopt a program for cooperation in the exploration and 
utilization of space in 1994. 
  A high-ranking representative of the Russian Space Agency, 
involved in organizing the committee's session, to be held in 
Moscow on June 2 and 3, told INTERFAX that the draft program 
envisaged allocations of 1.25 trillion rubles (in January 1994 
prices). However, this sum is likely to be increased to 2 
trillion rubles, he said. 
  In accordance with the project, another six satellites will 
be deployed within the framework of the program for creating the 
Gonets low-orbit global communication system (two experimental 
satellites of this series are on orbit already). In addition 
there are plans to launch the first four satellites of the 
Signal space communication system. 
  The program also provides for financing the development of 
heavy- duty boosters, including Energiya M and Proton M ones, 
and Start-1 and Start-1 super-light boosters. 

</TEXT>

