<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPD Bavarian Chairman: Coalition Possible </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPD Bavarian Chairman: Coalition Possible </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2604122194 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
26 Apr 94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> AU2604122194 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Bavarian SPD Does Not Rule Out </F>
Coalition With CSU"] 
  [Text] Munich, 25 Apr -- Several months before the 
Bavarian Landtag election, Social Democratic Party of Germany 
[SPD] faction chairman Schmid has mentioned the possibility of a 
coalition with the Christian Social Union [CSU]. If the CSU 
achieves only a relative majority instead of an absolute one 
and, if on the other hand, a coalition with the Greens and the 
Free Democratic Party is impossible, the SPD would be ready to 
form part of the government if only to prevent a coalition 
between the CSU and the Republikaner. At an SPD regional 
congress in Roding, Schmid called on the CSU to define its 
stance as a prerequisite for a coalition. The CSU, he said, must 
show that it is no longer the former Strauss party that could 
afford one scandal after another. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64189 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu083_h_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Republikaner Leader Said Hiding Role in Attack </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Republikaner Leader Said Hiding Role in Attack </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2604083194 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 25 Apr 94 p 16 </F>
<F P=103> AU2604083194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Attack Covered Up?"] </F>
  [Text] At the end of 1993, Republikaner boss Franz 
Schoenhuber is supposed to have found out that a leading member 
of the party was involved in an attack on a home for 
asylum-seekers in Bergheim near Cologne without having reported 
it to the police. The incident was, according to a protocol, 
raised at a meeting of the Republikaner executive committee for 
Mittlelrhein. Some party members were concerned that the 
Republikaner involvement in the attack might be covered up, so 
they sent a protocol of the meeting with a personal explanation 
to Schoenhuber and the chairman of the party's federal 
arbitration court, Munich Judge Johann Muehlberger. During the 
course of a search of the federal arbitration court last Friday 
[22 April] in Munich, the documents were found, according to the 
state prosecution service. Schoenhuber's office could not be 
searched, because as a member of the European Parliament, the 
Republikaner boss enjoys parliamentary immunity. The Cologne 
prosecution service is now considering having his immunity 
lifted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

