<H3> <TI>   Court Permits Hashish Use in Small Amounts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Court Permits Hashish Use in Small Amounts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2904103794 Berlin DIE WELT in German 29 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2904103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Karlsruhe: Hashish Consumption </F>
Permitted"] 
  [Text] Karlsruhe -- The possession and consumption of 
hashish and marijuana in small quantities will no longer be 
punishable. In a verdict released yesterday, the Constitutional 
Court in Karlsruhe decided that the authorities must turn a 
blind eye if cannabis products are procured or imported solely 
for occasional private use and if there is no danger to third 
parties. 
  In its decision, the Second Panel failed to specify the 
meaning of "small quantities" and "occasional private use," but 
placed the laender under an obligation to define these terms in 
order to coordinate the procedure for adopting new rules on 
discontinuing criminal proceedings. So far, only 
Schleswig-Holstein has defined these limits. Schleswig-Holstein 
courts consider a "small quantity" to mean up to 30 grams, on 
the assumption that this is a one-week supply for a single 
person. 
  At the same time, the Constitutional Court confirmed the ban 
on drugs as set down in the law on anesthetics, thus rejecting 
seven appeals from German courts that had said that permitting a 
limited use of drugs might not be in conformity with the 
Constitution, especially because of the different way of 
treating hashish and alcohol. 
  According to the Constitutional Court judges, the difference 
in sentences that can be meted out for the misuse of hashish, 
alcohol, and nicotine does not collide with the constitutional 
principle of equality. The misuse of alcohol involves dangers 
similar or even greater than those posed by the misuse of 
hashish and marijuana, but it should be borne in mind that there 
are many possible uses of alcohol, most of them not leading to a 
state of intoxication, whereas in the case of cannabis products, 
intoxication figures in first place. Needless to say, there is 
no "right to be intoxicated." 
  After a long period of time, the number of drug-induced 
deaths in Germany has once again clearly increased in the first 
quarter of the year. The Interior Ministry in Bonn said that 
the number of such deaths increased from 343 to 372 against the 
first quarter of 1993, an increase of 8.5 percent. The number 
of first-time consumers of hard drugs went up by 16.8 percent, 
reaching 2,250. 

</TEXT>

