<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Reacts to Criticism Over UN Council Seat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bonn Reacts to Criticism Over UN Council Seat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2804160794 Hamburg DPA in German 1511 GMT 28 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2804160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn/New York -- Bonn diplomats have reacted "very 
coolly" today to criticism by New Zealand concerning Germany's 
application for a seat in the UN Security Council. It is known 
that Germany wants a permanent seat in the highest 
decisionmaking body of the United Nations -- this has been 
repeatedly pointed out by Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Foreign 
Minister Klaus Kinkel -- and the Federal Government "is in close 
contact with UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali on this 
issue," a short statement stressed. 
  It was apparently considered embarrassing that, first, the 
criticism came from New Zealand Foreign Minister Don McKinnon, 
and, second, that McKinnon made his statement on Wednesday 
evening [27 April] as acting president of the Security Council. 
He described Japan as a "logical candidate" and expressed 
reservations vis-a-vis Germany, pointing out that there would be 
"too many white faces" if the Germans joined the UN Security 
Council. 
  The implementation of Germany's claim, which results from 
the 
changed world political map, will be difficult and only possible 
on a long-term basis because a decision must be made by the 
General Assembly -- after the presentation of the structural 
reform that does not yet exist. The secretary general is not 
entitled to vote. The 15-nation body has had five permanent 
members since 1945: The United States, Russia, China, France, 
and Great Britain. These five states also enjoy the right of 
veto in all decisions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

