<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Warns Against `Weakening' World Trade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rexrodt Warns Against `Weakening' World Trade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2904132694 Hamburg DPA in German 1155 GMT 29 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2904132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Munich -- Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt has 
warned against a weakening of the multilateral international 
trading system. He is concerned that the United States "wants 
to force trade concessions by means of one-sided sanctions," 
Rexrodt said in Munich on Friday [29 April] at the annual 
meeting of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in Germany. The 
multilateral trading system is the "indispensable umbrella, also 
for regional associations." 
  Rexrodt was optimistic that economic relations between 
Europe 
and the United States will be further expanded in 1994. He said 
he is thinking of multilateral agreements in the fields of 
steel, civil aviation, and financial services. Also, a 
multilateral agreement on restricting subsidies to the 
shipbuilding industry should be concluded in the near future. 
Rexrodt thinks that eastern Germany could be particularly 
important in the expansion of German-U.S. trade relations. This 
mainly has to do with East European markets being "right on our 
doorstep." 
  According to Rexrodt, there are over 1,400 U.S. companies 
represented in Germany at the moment, 275 of them in the new 
laender. They have created or preserved 50,000 jobs there and 
invested more than 8 billion German marks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

