<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Trade With East Europe Rising </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Trade With East Europe Rising </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2804151794 Hamburg DPA in German 1406 GMT 28 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2804151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DPA) -- The economic low point has been 
overcome in many countries in Eastern and Central Europe. This 
applies, above all, to the pioneers of reform -- the Czech 
Republic, Poland, and Hungary -- but also to Slovenia, Estonia, 
and, a bit farther behind, also to Slovakia, the Eastern and 
Central Europe Association (OMV) announced in Hamburg at its 
members' meeting on Thursday [28 April]. The importance of 
Eastern Europe for German foreign trade has increased. Foreign 
trade turnover with this region increased by at least 6 percent 
in 1993 to 88.2 billion German marks, while foreign trade as a 
whole decreased by 10 percent, the OMV annual report says. The 
share of trade with Eastern Europe in Germany's total foreign 
trade amounted to 7.7 percent. 
  The association is confident that the positive effects of 
trade and cooperation on economic growth will increasingly 
benefit also the weaker economies and will thus support the 
reform process, the report says. This applies to the CIS 
countries, even though in particular in Russia inflation had 
declined by the end of 1993. Romaine and Bulgaria, for their 
part, are orienting themselves toward market economy but do not 
yet show any real success, the report says. Members of the OMV 
are all leading German companies which conduct trade with 
Eastern and Central Europe or produce goods there. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64229 </DOCNO>
