<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kanther Urges Agreement With Turkey on Deported Kurds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kanther Urges Agreement With Turkey on Deported Kurds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2804172494 Hamburg DPA in German 1544 GMT 28 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2804172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mannheim -- Interior Minister Manfred Kanther 
(Christian Democratic Union) continues to urge the conclusion of 
an agreement with Turkey that will protect activists of the 
banned Workers Party of Kurdistan [PKK] who are deported to 
Turkey from the death penalty in their home country. The goal 
of the agreement is to guarantee sufficiently to authorities 
dealing with foreigners and to the courts that the Kurds are not 
facing the death penalty in the event of their deportation, 
Kanther told journalists in Mannheim today. However, the PKK is 
no "Robin Hood group," but a criminal organization, "and is 
being treated as such in Germany." 
  Kanther stressed that assurances by the Turkish Government 
that torture is not used by the state in dealing with people who 
think differently would be sufficient. The minister reported 
that after the ban of the PKK at the end of 1993, about 30 
affiliated organizations were also forbidden. The overwhelming 
majority of the Kurds living in Germany do not want to have 
anything to do with the PKK. 
  Bonn is interested in a peaceful settlement of the Kurdish 
issue in Turkey and feels sympathy for the maltreated people in 
the civil war zone. However, this has nothing to do with the 
prosecution of terrorism in Germany. "I do not care why 
somebody erects burning barricades on the roads. He is a 
criminal," the minister stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-64231 </DOCNO>
