<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Red Cross, Red Crescent Statement on Rwandan Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Red Cross, Red Crescent Statement on Rwandan Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004162094 Bern Swiss Radio International in English 1500 
GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3004162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern Swiss Radio International </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The mass exodus of refugees from war-torn Rwanda is 
continuing. The International Federation of Red Cross and Red 
Crescent Societies issued a statement in Geneva saying up to 
half a million people were believed to be heading for Tanzania. 
The federation said 300,000 refugees had already arrived in 
northwestern Tanzania. It described the exodus as the largest 
single movement of refugees in the federation's 75-year history. 
The Red Cross said it was sending an emergency aid team from 
Kenya to Tanzania, adding that massive amounts of relief 
supplies, including blankets and medicines, were needed 
urgently. The continuing flood of refugees comes after the UN 
Secretary General Butrus-Ghali appealed for a large military 
force to be sent to Rwanda to end the tribal carnage. 

</TEXT>

