<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   OECD Report Sees Science as `Victim' of Russian Reform </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    OECD Report Sees Science as `Victim' of Russian Reform </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2904164294 Paris AFP in English 1630 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2904164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 29 (AFP) -- Science and technology in 
Russia are going through a transition period and are among the 
first victims of the transformation and reform process there, 
according to a report just published by the OECD. 
  Under the Soviet system, Russia was as advanced in these 
fields as members of the Paris-based Organisation for Economic 
Cooperation and Development, which groups together the world's 
24 most developed countries. Now, it faces structural changes 
likely to retain only those aspects of science which can help 
the country's renewal, says the report, based on studies carried 
out in the second half of 1993. 
  Under the communists' centralised system the sector had 
developed out of all proportion to the country's Gross National 
Product, and spending on military applications must now be cut 
to allow civilian development, it said. Current priorities are 
modernisation of the health and social security system, energy, 
telecommunications and pollution. 
  Russian science, once cut off from the international 
community, can now benefit from the new contacts and 
collaboration with other countries, despite fears about a "brain 
drain," it comments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

