<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Denies Supporting RAF Withdrawal From FRG </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Denies Supporting RAF Withdrawal From FRG </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105002294 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 0001 GMT 1 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105002294 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Defence tonight dismissed as 
"nothing more than speculation" a report that senior RAF 
officers and planners have backed a plan to withdraw all British 
combat aircraft and helicopters from Germany. 
  The proposal is the most radical to emerge from a series of 
studies aimed at making a 1 billion pound cut in the 24 billion 
pound defence budget, according to THE OBSERVER which says it 
has seen a confidential six-page report. 
  If the Cabinet approves, nearly 80 fighter aircraft and 
6,000 
personnel would pull out of Germany by April 1996 as part of the 
latest round of defence cuts, the paper says. 
  It would end an RAF presence in Germany stretching back 
nearly half a century. 
  The paper quotes a senior RAF source saying: "In terms of 
the 
international situation, things have come on a long way since 
the reunification of Germany and there is a feeling that if we 
did need to go back it would not be that difficult." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

