<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry To Relax U.S. Bank Subsidiary Rules </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry To Relax U.S. Bank Subsidiary Rules </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2904140094 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 29 Apr 94 p 
16 </F>

<F P=103> AU2904140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["kr"-signed report: "Equal Rights With Europeans"] </F>
  [Text] Frankfurt/Main -- Subsidiaries of U.S. banks in 
Germany can expect regulations to relax considerably in the 
future. The Association of Foreign Banks reports that the 
Finance Ministry has completed a regulation based on an 
agreement between the governments and banking supervisory boards 
of the United States and Germany. This will give U.S. banks much 
the same rights as banks from European Union [EU] countries. 
The Association thinks that this regulation might guide other 
non-EU countries as well. 
  The Association of Foreign Banks, which has advocated 
extending the EU model to other non-European banks for some 
time, points out that U.S. banks will continue to be subject to 
approval and control by the Federal Banking Supervisory Board. 
The banks will, however, no longer be required to support risk 
assets by capital. 
  In the field of big loans, European regulations must be 
observed, which limit the risk for the individual debtor to 25 
percent of the bank's capital resources. What remains in force 
is the (costly) annual audit and a minimum capital of ECU5 
million per subsidiary, which, according to the association, is, 
however, insignificant in terms of banking supervision. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

